Cruise WS23203
This report maps the shallowest depth at which the interpolated dissolved oxygen field falls below a chosen threshold (anoxic/hypoxic boundary). Use the slider on the map to change the Oâ‚‚ threshold; grid cells are colored by depth in meters.


Observation and field summary
data.frame(
  casts = length(unique(obs$cast_id)),
  observation_rows = nrow(obs),
  field_grid_points = if (is.null(field)) NA_integer_ else nrow(field),
  oxygen_range_mg_l = if ("dissolved_oxygen" %in% names(obs)) {
    range(obs$dissolved_oxygen, na.rm = TRUE)
  } else {
    c(NA_real_, NA_real_)
  }
)


  casts observation_rows field_grid_points oxygen_range_mg_l
1    84             6994             23696            1.3486
2    84             6994             23696            5.9850

Anoxic depth map
Pan and zoom to explore where oxygen drops below the threshold. Each colored cell shows the shallowest depth (closest to the surface) where interpolated Oâ‚‚ is below the threshold â€” not the depth where Oâ‚‚ equals the threshold. When the threshold exceeds surface oxygen across the domain, expect uniform shallow depths (~2 m, the top of the interpolated grid). Hover a cell for its depth in meters. The color bar uses a fixed depth scale so colors are comparable across thresholds.


Interactive map of shallowest anoxic depth
if (is.null(field)) {
  cat(
    "Interpolated field not found. Run `make interpolate CRUISE=",
    params$batch_value,
    "` first.",
    sep = ""
  )
} else {
  map &lt;- plot_anoxic_depth_map(field, obs)
  if (is.null(map)) {
    cat("No interpolated field grid available for this cruise.")
  } else {
    map
  }
}

